<subSubSection id="75A134AFCC3DFFEDFF4BF979FD337239" pageId="16" pageNumber="151" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="3D046724CC3DFFEDFF4BF979FD337239" blockId="16.[136,776,1466,1861]" pageId="16" pageNumber="151">
Remarks: There are no recent specimens of this subfamily known from 
<collectingCountry id="45AC27B4CC3DFFEDFF78F95DFEAC73C9" box="[187,287,1696,1717]" name="Singapore" pageId="16" pageNumber="151">Singapore</collectingCountry>
. It is quite likely that Bleeker’s original record from 
<collectingCountry id="45AC27B4CC3DFFEDFF4BF940FF5A73AE" box="[136,233,1725,1746]" name="Singapore" pageId="16" pageNumber="151">Singapore</collectingCountry>
(which has consequently been cited by others) is in error, as there has never been suitable habitat for sicydiine gobiids in 
<collectingCountry id="45AC27B4CC3DFFEDFF4BF90AFF5F7270" box="[136,236,1783,1804]" name="Singapore" pageId="16" pageNumber="151">Singapore</collectingCountry>
. These fishes require fast steep freshwater streams with access to the sea, while all rivers and streams in 
<collectingCountry id="45AC27B4CC3DFFEDFD8FF8E9FD037255" box="[588,688,1812,1833]" name="Singapore" pageId="16" pageNumber="151">Singapore</collectingCountry>
, past and present, are low–lying and relatively slow–moving.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
